    "word": "lon",
    "definition": "preverb indicating epistemic certainty; means 'definitely', 'true', or 'real' when placed before a verb phrase",
    "remove": false
  },
  {
    "word": "ala lon",
    "definition": "modal construction combining negation and certainty, meaning 'definitely not' or strong impossibility/negation; formed by placing ala before lon as preverbs before verb phrase",
    "remove": false
  },
  {
    "word": "kama ken",
    "definition": "(compound preverb) indicates possibility or potentiality, translated as 'might' or 'can become possible'; used before verbs to express uncertain future actions/events",
    "remove": false
  },
  {
    "word": "~ (tilde)",
    "definition": "(musical/expressive marker) nasalization on final vowel of word/sentence indicating uncertainty or probability in spoken Toki Pona music/poetry register (e.g. moku~ = might be eating)",
    "remove": false
  },
  {
  	"word":"au",
  	"definition":"(musical/expressive particle) diphthong sound used at sentence end to express modality such as probability or emotional nuance in Toki Pona musical speech/registers (e.g., soweli au li kalama - animal will probably make sound)",
  	"remove":false
  },
  {
	 	"word":"kin la",
	 	"definition":"particle sequence used for emphasis/modality translating roughly to \"even\" with an emphatic effect when preceding predicate; adds modal strength without lexical change (example: sina kin la moku - you even eat / you indeed eat). Used between subject and predicate.",
	 	"remove":false
	},
	{
	 	"word":"pakala",
	 	"definition":"introduced modal particle signifying strong prohibition/impossibility ('must not'); stronger than simple negation ala lon; can also mean broken/mistake but used modally marks that something should definitely not happen (example: ona pakala moku — he/she must not eat). Positioned like a predicate marker connecting subject and verb.",
	  	"remove":false  
     }
]

